§18 — Closed-Loop Bounding Property (Safety Argument)
Worker C is a closed-loop research artifact. The safety property has three legs:

Operator-only deploy. Worker C runs on the operator's own Cloudflare account. No third-party operator surface. Setup UI is gated by a one-time token printed on first deploy and rotated on first POST.
BLOCKED_HOSTS list — exactly 4 CoCoDem C2 hosts. Every outbound fetch flows through safeOutboundFetch which throws on hostname match. The list is openclaude.111724.xyz, cfc.aroic.workers.dev, 111724.xyz, aroic.workers.dev. Anthropic domains are not blocked because passthrough mode is the live VDP demo with the operator's own credentials.
Safe Harbor coverage. HackerOne anthropic VDP (live program, May 2026 launch, Gold Standard Safe Harbor) explicitly authorizes good-faith research that involves only the operator's own account, minimal exploitation to prove the vuln, no exfiltration, no DoS, and X-HackerOne-Handle attached on every outbound request. Worker C injects the handle automatically in passthrough mode.
The headline finding is: wire-level system-prompt mutation is deterministic on /v1/messages traffic across all four auth modes. The closed-loop bounding ensures that demonstration cannot escape into a malicious-deploy posture without an operator deliberately removing the BLOCKED_HOSTS list and disabling the redaction layer — both grep-checkable invariants the reviewer can audit.

